On the contrary, we have seen that the segments have gradually undergone important changes not only in their mutual position but even in their external form. When studying the phenomena of segmentation one get-s the impression that the segments alternately attract and repel each other, and that the highest degree of attraction occurs when the nuclei after a completed segmentation have obtained their rounded distinct form and are in a state of repose.
